MTF,<br><br>
I laugh out loud in front of my screen from many of theomments that I have read here.  It makes feel good and proud.  They are good laughs and will be treasured for many years to come.  I am very proud of all you folks, who handle the subject of Vietnam with both seriousness and humor.  That's a good sign for all of us.  <br><br>
Jay Leno was quoted in an old Parade Magazine article a half dozen or so years ago.  He said that Vietnam was a subject that couldn't be made fun of.  (my paraphrase)<br><br>
Ed, serious, for a moment, I have been thinking, and rethinking PTSD.  I am under the impression from your responses on this post that you know a lot about it from your work.   I have belonged to a vet's group in the past.  I am still thinking about what I want to write, but initially (sp) what I want think.  My question is how can we (I) can associate PTSD with what happens in the rest of our lives.  What are common symptoms? etc.  These thoughts are still bouncing around in my head.  I'm not sure if they are worthwhile yet or not, but will soon make the attempt.<br><br>
I can't end this message seriously.  Therefore, I cahnging my &quot;call sign&quot; to MLMB&quot; -- mom loves me best.<br><br>
Paul<br><br>
PS -- My best to you and all.  Hi Gary.<br><br>
